1
00:00:08,427 --> 00:00:12,187
On the far side of the world is a remote tropical island,

2
00:00:12,846 --> 00:00:16,341
carved by waterfalls and covered in thick jungle.

3
00:00:17,554 --> 00:00:18,097
New Guinea.

4
00:00:19,410 --> 00:00:22,803
At its heart are rugged mountains and deep gorges.

5
00:00:23,605 --> 00:00:26,233
It's one of the least explored corners of our planet.

6
00:00:29,152 --> 00:00:32,145
Over nine months, a team of scientists,

7
00:00:32,578 --> 00:00:36,661
adventurers and filmmakers have been on an expedition into the unknown.

8
00:00:40,624 --> 00:00:45,083
Helped by a local tribe, they've found some of the strangest creatures on Earth.

9
00:00:45,417 --> 00:00:46,751
Look at that.

10
00:00:52,892 --> 00:00:54,791
Oh, wow, wow wow, wow! Jeepers!

11
00:00:55,433 --> 00:00:59,479
Now, they're leaving base camp and striking out in two directions.

12
00:01:00,685 --> 00:01:03,151
One team is venturing to an erupting volcano.

13
00:01:05,399 --> 00:01:09,627
Oh! It's being thrown a kilometre into the air.

14
00:01:10,877 --> 00:01:14,015
The other team will journey deep into an unexplored crater,

15
00:01:14,619 --> 00:01:18,629
hoping to discover spectacular animals never seen by the outside world.

16
00:01:19,124 --> 00:01:20,413
What is that?

17
00:01:23,898 --> 00:01:25,831
Absolutely out of this world.

18
00:01:26,600 --> 00:01:28,361
Good God, look at that.

19
00:01:28,892 --> 00:01:30,874
And they make a dramatic discovery.

20
00:01:31,560 --> 00:01:34,362
That is the biggest I have ever seen.

21
00:01:34,650 --> 00:01:36,923
Oh, my word, have a look at this.

22
00:02:03,587 --> 00:02:04,235
New Guinea,

23
00:02:05,590 --> 00:02:08,729
the largest and most mountainous tropical island on Earth,

24
00:02:09,549 --> 00:02:13,182
so impenetrable, large areas remain uncharted.

25
00:02:26,431 --> 00:02:31,710
At the heart of this vast island is Mount Bosavi, an extinct volcano.

26
00:02:33,242 --> 00:02:34,490
Oh!

27
00:02:35,177 --> 00:02:37,214
Climber and naturalist Steve Backshall

28
00:02:37,749 --> 00:02:41,093
is leading the first-ever expedition deep into its huge crater.

29
00:02:41,831 --> 00:02:44,635
This is what we do expeditions for, places like this.

30
00:02:45,474 --> 00:02:49,018
Unimaginably beautiful, and totally unexplored.

31
00:02:50,335 --> 00:02:52,841
Very few places in the world left like Mount Bosavi.

32
00:02:55,724 --> 00:02:59,479
Outside the crater, they've already found new types of frogs,

33
00:02:59,719 --> 00:03:01,196
lizards and insects.

34
00:03:01,716 --> 00:03:05,207
But inside, there could be unknown large mammals,

35
00:03:05,588 --> 00:03:07,274
hidden from the rest of the world.

36
00:03:10,451 --> 00:03:12,215
These are the walls of the crater rim.

37
00:03:13,350 --> 00:03:16,540
It's an almost perfect volcanic cone.

38
00:03:16,880 --> 00:03:20,651
And what we're looking at now is the inside wall.

39
00:03:23,725 --> 00:03:26,624
It's no wonder everyone's so excited about getting in this place.

40
00:03:27,844 --> 00:03:29,681
It's absolutely epic.

41
00:03:31,840 --> 00:03:35,700
Discovering new mammals in the crater would put Bosavi on the map

42
00:03:36,808 --> 00:03:38,498
and hopefully lead to its protection.

43
00:03:39,618 --> 00:03:42,571
Loggers are just south of the mountain and moving closer.

44
00:03:52,334 --> 00:03:55,891
High on the crater rim, there's a small gap in the trees.

45
00:04:02,111 --> 00:04:05,410
The local Kasua tribe have agreed to meet Steve here.

46
00:04:08,247 --> 00:04:10,753
They've given their blessing for the team to enter this,

47
00:04:11,462 --> 00:04:12,559
their most sacred land.

48
00:04:16,012 --> 00:04:20,795
The head of the clan that owns Bosavi is bringing up some magic,

49
00:04:20,820 --> 00:04:22,539
he's singing us into the crater,

50
00:04:22,611 --> 00:04:25,945
he's opening it for us so that the nature will be

51
00:04:26,025 --> 00:04:29,150
allowing us in there and not angry with us for going into the crater.

52
00:04:29,744 --> 00:04:31,463
And we have to walk under the magic stick.

53
00:04:47,945 --> 00:04:50,167
Even the Kasua rarely come here.

54
00:04:51,577 --> 00:04:54,332
Fiercely territorial, this is the first time

55
00:04:54,397 --> 00:04:57,036
they've guided an expedition into their magical crater.

56
00:05:01,159 --> 00:05:03,701
It's very steep and very wet.

57
00:05:06,815 --> 00:05:08,917
Have to go very slowly.

58
00:05:11,574 --> 00:05:11,942
Well done.

59
00:05:13,695 --> 00:05:16,419
The clouds are just coming up to meet us.

60
00:05:17,132 --> 00:05:17,956
Down there...

61
00:05:19,285 --> 00:05:21,005
is a genuine lost world.

62
00:05:23,697 --> 00:05:26,393
Just don't want to take a wrong step here, anywhere.

63
00:05:33,297 --> 00:05:35,712
They need to find somewhere to build a rough camp.

64
00:05:36,463 --> 00:05:38,956
Only then can they call in the rest of the team.

65
00:05:44,538 --> 00:05:47,351
Outside the crater, at the foot of Mount Bosavi,

66
00:05:47,891 --> 00:05:49,510
the old base camp is packed up.

67
00:05:51,570 --> 00:05:54,605
For now, intrepid bug expert George McGavin

68
00:05:55,397 --> 00:05:56,857
is venturing off on a side trip.

69
00:05:59,761 --> 00:06:00,527
We're going.

70
00:06:02,020 --> 00:06:03,780
Very excited about this indeed.

71
00:06:07,634 --> 00:06:11,569
George will be searching for wildlife on the slopes of a very different volcano.

72
00:06:12,570 --> 00:06:13,455
One that's erupting.

73
00:06:19,126 --> 00:06:22,637
It's 700 miles to the east, on the island of New Britain.

74
00:06:23,336 --> 00:06:26,682
Recently it's been quiet, but it could go off at any time.

75
00:06:40,822 --> 00:06:42,910
Mile after mile is choked with ash,

76
00:06:43,624 --> 00:06:47,374
but George is keen to see what, if anything, can survive here.

77
00:06:54,778 --> 00:06:56,280
At first, it appears barren.

78
00:06:58,425 --> 00:07:00,779
It's more hell on Earth than wildlife hotspot.

79
00:07:01,794 --> 00:07:02,678
Basically, it's just...

80
00:07:03,457 --> 00:07:06,584
just covered in ash, and there isn't anything growing at all.

81
00:07:06,861 --> 00:07:08,770
It's all dead, and decaying.

82
00:07:09,804 --> 00:07:10,965
It smells of sulphur.

83
00:07:29,515 --> 00:07:31,018
George's first discovery

84
00:07:32,664 --> 00:07:34,693
is perilously close to the crater.

85
00:07:39,334 --> 00:07:44,026
This is a beautiful bird. It's a brahminy kite.

86
00:07:44,550 --> 00:07:46,592
The fact that it's flying around here

87
00:07:46,720 --> 00:07:49,935
means that there has to be enough food for it to eat.

88
00:07:50,690 --> 00:07:55,830
Although I can't see much for it to eat, but it clearly is hunting.

89
00:07:57,770 --> 00:07:59,941
If it's not careful it'll be hit by a rock in a minute.

90
00:08:00,341 --> 00:08:03,831
It seems to be flying very close to the crater there.

91
00:08:06,710 --> 00:08:08,383
A bird of prey is a promising sign,

92
00:08:09,482 --> 00:08:12,457
but George must also keep an eye out for flying rocks.

93
00:08:18,680 --> 00:08:21,028
Mount Bosavi was once an active volcano.

94
00:08:21,859 --> 00:08:26,114
It stopped erupting 200,000 years ago, and rainforest took over.

95
00:08:27,246 --> 00:08:32,170
Since then it's remained unchanged, untouched and unexplored.

96
00:08:38,900 --> 00:08:42,082
Steve and the team are following a river to the heart of the crater.

97
00:08:42,959 --> 00:08:43,812
It's slow going,

98
00:08:44,490 --> 00:08:47,036
but it's the best way to cover ground in a dense jungle.

99
00:08:59,790 --> 00:09:01,080
Not a bad spot.

100
00:09:01,527 --> 00:09:02,067
Good spot.

101
00:09:04,235 --> 00:09:06,668
- Shall we try and get a tarp up before this rain starts? - Yeah, yeah.

102
00:09:08,389 --> 00:09:09,587
Shelter is essential.

103
00:09:10,673 --> 00:09:12,830
New Guinea is one of the wettest places on Earth.

104
00:09:14,892 --> 00:09:16,558
It can pour for days on end.

105
00:09:32,380 --> 00:09:35,368
The Kasua tribe come from the outer slopes of the mountain.

106
00:09:37,745 --> 00:09:41,700
These old men remember a time before any contact with the outside world,

107
00:09:42,424 --> 00:09:44,024
when their clan were cannibals.

108
00:09:52,079 --> 00:09:56,542
They said their fathers were great warriors and used to battle with nearby clans quite often,

109
00:09:56,589 --> 00:09:59,857
but they also have, it seems, very vivid memories

110
00:09:59,882 --> 00:10:02,436
of them actually killing and eating their enemies.

111
00:10:03,631 --> 00:10:07,261
The chief here is describing how he remembers them cutting the thighs

112
00:10:07,527 --> 00:10:10,518
into halves and putting them on stone fires to cook them,

113
00:10:11,040 --> 00:10:14,403
and it seems that it was not so much a ceremonial thing

114
00:10:14,516 --> 00:10:17,842
but actually just for the meat, for the protein, for the fact that meat was

115
00:10:17,902 --> 00:10:22,092
quite scarce around here and to have human meat was as good as anything.

116
00:10:28,408 --> 00:10:32,934
They no longer eat people, but they are still expert hunters,

117
00:10:33,544 --> 00:10:35,342
totally at home in this jungle.

118
00:10:36,242 --> 00:10:39,150
Without the tribe, the expedition would be lost.

119
00:10:45,109 --> 00:10:49,202
200,000 years ago, Mount Bosavi would have looked like this,

120
00:10:49,966 --> 00:10:51,241
hostile and desolate.

121
00:10:52,601 --> 00:10:55,864
But George knows better than anyone where to find signs of life.

122
00:10:59,633 --> 00:11:02,093
This is definitely where I'd expect to find something.

123
00:11:04,102 --> 00:11:05,759
Oh! Aha!

124
00:11:06,280 --> 00:11:09,576
Look at that, baby! Look at that.

125
00:11:10,540 --> 00:11:12,404
A rhinoceros beetle larva.

126
00:11:12,544 --> 00:11:15,896
It's a whopper. Look at that.

127
00:11:16,820 --> 00:11:18,499
Head's up here, big jaws,

128
00:11:19,280 --> 00:11:23,381
and they just eat this decaying wood and fibre.

129
00:11:24,098 --> 00:11:26,073
Going to have to put him down somewhere.

130
00:11:26,906 --> 00:11:29,830
Put him on there while I attack the rest of this.

131
00:11:31,747 --> 00:11:32,124
Ah!

132
00:11:33,857 --> 00:11:34,550
Ha ha!

133
00:11:36,201 --> 00:11:37,201
There's the adult.

134
00:11:39,885 --> 00:11:40,640
So there...

135
00:11:41,939 --> 00:11:45,092
is what this will become eventually.

136
00:11:45,960 --> 00:11:46,869
Rhinoceros beetle.

137
00:11:47,873 --> 00:11:48,657
Absolutely brilliant.

138
00:11:50,221 --> 00:11:54,836
Some creatures endure the volcano, others actually seek it out.

139
00:11:56,492 --> 00:12:01,089
I can see two birds that look like sort of large hens.

140
00:12:02,865 --> 00:12:05,408
They're megapode birds, and, bizarrely,

141
00:12:05,983 --> 00:12:07,983
they depend on this active volcano.

142
00:12:16,662 --> 00:12:21,959
In the Bosavi crater, Steve and the trackers fan out to explore for the first time.

143
00:12:27,736 --> 00:12:32,657
Steve will climb, crawl and swim the rivers to find out what lives here.

144
00:12:37,566 --> 00:12:40,043
Chief Sigaro and the trackers search the high ground.

145
00:12:40,743 --> 00:12:43,642
In the valley, Steve stumbles across something remarkable.

146
00:12:44,406 --> 00:12:46,341
Absolutely out of this world.

147
00:12:48,125 --> 00:12:50,760
It's a rare kind of kangaroo that climbs trees.

148
00:12:51,533 --> 00:12:53,701
And it's probably never seen people before.

149
00:12:54,441 --> 00:12:57,261
The fact that this animal is totally unafraid of humans,

150
00:12:57,286 --> 00:12:58,794
just wandered straight past us,

151
00:12:59,364 --> 00:13:03,626
 means the wildlife here has never been hunted before — it hasn't seen people before.

152
00:13:03,993 --> 00:13:08,024
I never expected to have a tree kangaroo on our first morning that we've been up and running.

153
00:13:08,887 --> 00:13:13,908
This is a phenomenal start, a phenomenal start.

154
00:13:18,365 --> 00:13:21,451
It's time to call in wildlife cameraman Gordon Buchanan.

155
00:13:22,746 --> 00:13:25,723
Gordon's mission is to film any animal the team finds.

156
00:13:30,040 --> 00:13:33,605
Many of the rainforests that I've been to before are quite flat.

157
00:13:34,544 --> 00:13:39,122
This is a very, very difficult terrain, and without a doubt

158
00:13:39,147 --> 00:13:43,288
there'll be species down there that are completely unknown to science.

159
00:13:46,385 --> 00:13:49,387
Finding and filming a large mammal that no-one knew existed

160
00:13:49,846 --> 00:13:51,406
would be the greatest prize of all.

161
00:13:52,197 --> 00:13:55,478
But in this rugged terrain, it's a daunting prospect.

162
00:14:12,403 --> 00:14:14,349
Gordon has with him two scientists,

163
00:14:14,374 --> 00:14:17,367
who will help to identify any mammals the team discovers.

164
00:14:24,400 --> 00:14:28,397
Muse Opiang and Kris Helgen set up their makeshift jungle lab.

165
00:14:32,164 --> 00:14:34,142
But Gordon has no time to unpack.

166
00:14:34,501 --> 00:14:37,121
One of the trackers has found another tree kangaroo.

167
00:14:40,910 --> 00:14:43,703
We've just had a shout from one of the local guys, shouting "toonape"

168
00:14:43,728 --> 00:14:46,540
which is the tree kangaroo, so I'm hoping to catch up before it goes.

169
00:14:47,068 --> 00:14:48,191
As quick as we can.

170
00:14:50,368 --> 00:14:50,675
Ah!

171
00:14:56,257 --> 00:14:57,219
Oh, yeah, he's here.

172
00:14:57,839 --> 00:14:59,623
Oh, goodness me.

173
00:15:00,647 --> 00:15:04,107
It's a glorious tree kangaroo, just literally six,

174
00:15:04,132 --> 00:15:05,830
seven metres in front of me.

175
00:15:07,814 --> 00:15:11,157
For me, these animals are the height of weird.

176
00:15:11,182 --> 00:15:13,799
They're one of the strangest animals that live in this forest,

177
00:15:14,167 --> 00:15:17,706
I think because they're recognisable, they're kangaroos,

178
00:15:17,731 --> 00:15:19,857
but these kangaroos live in the trees.

179
00:15:21,334 --> 00:15:24,558
It's like a cross between a koala bear and a kangaroo.

180
00:15:28,605 --> 00:15:30,165
Oh, he's very cute.

181
00:15:34,076 --> 00:15:35,940
Really short, stocky build.

182
00:15:37,254 --> 00:15:40,504
Huge claws. The nails must be about two to three inches long.

183
00:15:42,645 --> 00:15:45,076
Oh, yes, he's eating, oh, lovely.

184
00:15:46,193 --> 00:15:47,497
Now that's a really good sign,

185
00:15:47,522 --> 00:15:50,916
because animals that feed are relaxed.

186
00:15:56,112 --> 00:15:59,412
100%, this animal will never have seen a human being before,

187
00:15:59,845 --> 00:16:04,055
so that's why we're able to stay as close as this, as we are.

188
00:16:08,762 --> 00:16:10,762
Tree kangaroos are incredibly rare.

189
00:16:11,563 --> 00:16:14,790
Outside the crater, they're heavily hunted and afraid of people.

190
00:16:15,558 --> 00:16:18,102
Inside, they aren't bothered by humans.

191
00:16:24,402 --> 00:16:26,821
George's volcano could go off at any time,

192
00:16:27,754 --> 00:16:29,236
but he's too engrossed to care.

193
00:16:31,637 --> 00:16:34,443
He's hot on the trail of the peculiar megapode bird.

194
00:16:37,449 --> 00:16:40,613
One of them's just landed really clumsily on that branch

195
00:16:40,638 --> 00:16:42,714
and thrown up a whole shower of ash.

196
00:16:44,040 --> 00:16:48,442
It's very hard to get close to these birds, they're very skittish.

197
00:16:59,255 --> 00:17:01,835
I reckon if we inch forward to this ridge...

198
00:17:12,974 --> 00:17:18,135
They've landed, they're down. There's two just on the ground over there.

199
00:17:20,954 --> 00:17:25,368
Unlike any other bird, megapodes bury their eggs deep in the ash,

200
00:17:25,928 --> 00:17:28,266
and let the warmth of the volcano incubate them.

201
00:17:42,637 --> 00:17:45,532
The megapode egg-laying site is just down there.

202
00:17:47,094 --> 00:17:48,727
If George is to find an egg,

203
00:17:49,307 --> 00:17:52,826
he must wait for them to finish and hope the volcano stays quiet.

204
00:18:03,120 --> 00:18:07,424
Mount Bosavi is extinct now, but the eruption left behind

205
00:18:07,449 --> 00:18:11,729
this crater four miles wide, enclosed by towering walls.

206
00:18:23,821 --> 00:18:25,945
Steve's still out exploring the river...

207
00:18:28,035 --> 00:18:30,222
..but it's not just the rocks that are treacherous.

208
00:18:31,890 --> 00:18:35,080
This plant is making life here absolute hell.

209
00:18:35,427 --> 00:18:38,412
They're everywhere and they're called a stinging tree.

210
00:18:39,507 --> 00:18:46,487
On the underside of each leaf are thousands of little hairs all filled with poison,

211
00:18:46,747 --> 00:18:51,609
and the sting, actually, can carry on going for two or three months.

212
00:18:52,766 --> 00:18:53,388
Ow!

213
00:18:57,993 --> 00:18:58,812
Serves me right!

214
00:19:03,498 --> 00:19:05,484
Every little stream is investigated.

215
00:19:06,357 --> 00:19:08,264
Any one might hide a surprise.

216
00:19:11,751 --> 00:19:16,145
Sticking up out of this vine are lots of little twigs,

217
00:19:17,067 --> 00:19:18,301
except they're not twigs,

218
00:19:18,326 --> 00:19:21,640
they're leeches, just waiting for something to walk past.

219
00:19:22,086 --> 00:19:24,868
They're switched on by warmth and also by

220
00:19:24,981 --> 00:19:28,620
the carbon dioxide you breathe out, and if I just breathe on them...

221
00:19:32,943 --> 00:19:35,463
Look at that. Instantly feeling around

222
00:19:36,449 --> 00:19:37,228
for the source of it.

223
00:19:38,128 --> 00:19:39,390
Looking for a blood meal.

224
00:19:40,648 --> 00:19:41,661
I hate them!

225
00:19:42,962 --> 00:19:44,222
Steve may hate them,

226
00:19:44,882 --> 00:19:48,332
but leeches mean there must be lots of warm-blooded animals to feed on.

227
00:19:54,053 --> 00:19:56,521
It's an encouraging sign for the mammal experts.

228
00:19:57,341 --> 00:19:59,320
Kris Helgen, from the Smithsonian Museum,

229
00:19:59,846 --> 00:20:02,904
is the world authority on identifying new mammal species.

230
00:20:04,680 --> 00:20:07,660
From the river, Steve's brought in a fragment of skull.

231
00:20:09,930 --> 00:20:12,478
You can see the pre-molar's fallen out and that corresponds to this too.

232
00:20:13,873 --> 00:20:15,722
When you're studying mammals,

233
00:20:15,808 --> 00:20:19,030
the dentition, the arrangement of the teeth, the amount of teeth that are there,

234
00:20:19,055 --> 00:20:22,951
that's one of the most important things in figuring out what something is.

235
00:20:22,976 --> 00:20:24,722
We're really lucky as mammologists,

236
00:20:24,756 --> 00:20:28,271
because if we find a single tooth or a single piece of skull,

237
00:20:28,331 --> 00:20:30,137
we can often tell exactly which species it is.

238
00:20:30,768 --> 00:20:34,021
This is a mystery still, but I'd like to find the animal

239
00:20:34,642 --> 00:20:35,984
that goes along with this skull.

240
00:20:36,617 --> 00:20:38,773
Let's see what we can find in the forest.

241
00:20:38,898 --> 00:20:44,137
Wow. So I could be holding in my hand the skull of a new species of mammal.

242
00:20:45,414 --> 00:20:47,727
Let's see where it takes us.

243
00:20:49,215 --> 00:20:53,897
The skull could belong a new type of cuscus, a small bear-like creatrue .

244
00:20:54,425 --> 00:20:56,242
The team had gone out to search the forest.

245
00:21:00,295 --> 00:21:03,605
At the volcano, George's wait is nearly over.

246
00:21:05,469 --> 00:21:07,875
Now there should be eggs buried somewhere in the ash.

247
00:21:11,438 --> 00:21:14,361
I think the birds have finished laying now, so with any luck,

248
00:21:14,690 --> 00:21:17,422
I should find some freshly-scraped ground,

249
00:21:17,729 --> 00:21:20,362
which might indicate where the eggs are laid.

250
00:21:22,979 --> 00:21:24,387
Once the megapodes leave,

251
00:21:25,060 --> 00:21:27,679
the volcano will keep the eggs warm until they hatch.

252
00:21:31,758 --> 00:21:34,233
This looks like exactly where they've been.

253
00:21:35,366 --> 00:21:37,725
They could be as much as two metres underground.

254
00:21:39,920 --> 00:21:42,646
I reckon down there is an egg.

255
00:21:48,350 --> 00:21:51,936
When the chicks hatch out, alone and in the pitch black,

256
00:21:52,438 --> 00:21:53,982
they claw their way to the surface.

257
00:21:59,985 --> 00:22:04,490
Well, I'm almost at... as far as I can reach down.

258
00:22:13,279 --> 00:22:15,388
Yes! I think I've got one! Ha ha!

259
00:22:17,384 --> 00:22:20,337
There is a megapode egg.

260
00:22:22,656 --> 00:22:23,669
The size of it!

261
00:22:24,886 --> 00:22:28,721
The chicks emerge well developed, fending for themselves from day one.

262
00:22:29,681 --> 00:22:31,027
They never know their parents.

263
00:22:31,871 --> 00:22:35,557
What a tough start to life in this tough environment.

264
00:22:43,074 --> 00:22:44,329
That was almost a scrambled egg then!

265
00:22:46,784 --> 00:22:48,605
George returns the egg to safety,

266
00:22:49,339 --> 00:22:51,985
but the volcano is getting ready to blood.

267
00:23:00,619 --> 00:23:02,414
That's getting a little too close for comfort.

268
00:23:05,476 --> 00:23:08,006
That's coming halfway down the slope now, easily.

269
00:23:18,627 --> 00:23:19,788
Nice. Hold on there.

270
00:23:20,670 --> 00:23:23,928
In the crater, Gordon and Kris are still out searching.

271
00:23:24,388 --> 00:23:26,103
No, no. It doesn't really go in.

272
00:23:27,025 --> 00:23:27,898
That broken bit's hollow.

273
00:23:29,891 --> 00:23:31,777
They're looking for the mystery cuscus,

274
00:23:32,320 --> 00:23:34,491
the mammal whose skull Steve found earlier.

275
00:23:36,193 --> 00:23:36,997
Have a look in there.

276
00:23:44,875 --> 00:23:45,590
Oh, crikey!

277
00:23:46,481 --> 00:23:48,195
- You got somebody? Somebody's home? - Yeah.

278
00:23:49,645 --> 00:23:51,725
Something is holed up in an old tree trunk,

279
00:23:52,338 --> 00:23:54,131
but it's too deep to see what it is.

280
00:23:54,628 --> 00:23:56,803
- Just sitting there. - Let me have a look in there!

281
00:23:58,550 --> 00:23:59,363
Have a look.

282
00:24:00,124 --> 00:24:01,487
God, that's the weirdest thing.

283
00:24:03,670 --> 00:24:04,470
Oh, wow.

284
00:24:07,572 --> 00:24:09,655
Gordon will have to wait for it to emerge.

285
00:24:10,365 --> 00:24:12,811
What I want to do is just set up, maybe over there,

286
00:24:13,311 --> 00:24:15,999
wait for it to get dark and see what happens.

287
00:24:16,608 --> 00:24:17,414
Quite exciting.

288
00:24:20,603 --> 00:24:22,043
If it is the new type of cuscus,

289
00:24:22,552 --> 00:24:24,723
Gordon doesn't want to miss his chance to film it.

290
00:24:28,066 --> 00:24:29,601
It's looking pretty good.

291
00:24:30,208 --> 00:24:31,935
Just see what happens once I climb down.

292
00:24:32,939 --> 00:24:35,062
A small camera pointing into the tree stump

293
00:24:35,604 --> 00:24:37,612
will warn him if the animal starts to climb up.

294
00:24:41,014 --> 00:24:43,504
He can then film from a distance without disturbing it.

295
00:24:44,383 --> 00:24:48,822
The problem with this situation is just the waiting for the animal to come out.

296
00:24:48,909 --> 00:24:50,151
It will definitely come out, it's just a case of when.

297
00:25:02,013 --> 00:25:03,533
The long wait begins.

298
00:25:07,782 --> 00:25:09,762
George must beat a hasty retreat.

299
00:25:10,191 --> 00:25:11,959
His wildlife survey could be over.

300
00:25:12,633 --> 00:25:14,009
The volcano is kicking off.

301
00:25:26,532 --> 00:25:29,291
It's throwing out massive amounts of red hot rock,

302
00:25:30,151 --> 00:25:34,303
and you can hear the bangs as they hit the ground, the great thumps.

303
00:25:36,448 --> 00:25:37,480
Look at that.

304
00:25:40,994 --> 00:25:43,934
Oh, this is incredible.

305
00:25:43,959 --> 00:25:48,586
I mean, it's fantastic to be this close to an active volcano.

306
00:25:48,828 --> 00:25:52,030
It's throwing out massive amounts of hot rock, red-hot rock.

307
00:25:52,163 --> 00:25:53,993
It's throwing them a kilometre in the air.

308
00:25:55,532 --> 00:25:59,928
That is one of the most spectacular sights I think I've ever seen.

309
00:26:02,763 --> 00:26:08,487
This is an infra-red camera, so it's able to see all the hot stuff,

310
00:26:08,514 --> 00:26:10,233
which the big cameras can't see.

311
00:26:12,499 --> 00:26:17,144
When this thing erupts, you can feel the shockwaves hitting you.

312
00:26:18,451 --> 00:26:22,616
That thing is on top of a chamber of molten rock

313
00:26:22,672 --> 00:26:26,742
three kilometres wide and three kilometres deep.

314
00:26:27,313 --> 00:26:30,247
I mean, it's just...terrifying.

315
00:26:30,941 --> 00:26:32,909
But to be absolutely honest with you,

316
00:26:32,942 --> 00:26:35,817
I'm actually feeling quite apprehensive,

317
00:26:36,124 --> 00:26:40,431
because this is a force that...

318
00:26:40,456 --> 00:26:43,013
just is too immense to even think about.

319
00:26:43,394 --> 00:26:48,082
You couldn't speed away from this in a hurry. You'd be toast.

320
00:26:49,384 --> 00:26:51,544
Good grief!

321
00:26:57,222 --> 00:27:00,503
Four hours on, and still no sign of the unknown mammal.

322
00:27:02,454 --> 00:27:04,760
I don't often feel as if I've got the upper hand on an animal.

323
00:27:04,969 --> 00:27:06,488
I think in this case I do,

324
00:27:06,635 --> 00:27:09,583
because I can see the monitor of the camera that's looking straight down.

325
00:27:10,230 --> 00:27:11,920
So it gives me a bit of warning.

326
00:27:12,757 --> 00:27:16,212
If he's a bit agitated from me looking down into that tree stump earlier on,

327
00:27:16,591 --> 00:27:19,773
he might just shoot out and I won't get any shots of him,

328
00:27:19,805 --> 00:27:21,593
but at least that camera up there,

329
00:27:22,246 --> 00:27:24,592
I can see the moment he starts to climb up.

330
00:27:25,648 --> 00:27:29,413
This is really exciting, because other than just two little eyes,

331
00:27:29,667 --> 00:27:31,406
I just don't know what's in there.

332
00:27:31,666 --> 00:27:35,181
It's a mammal of some sort, but who knows what it is?

333
00:27:39,724 --> 00:27:41,183
OK, he's starting to come, he's starting to come.

334
00:27:43,103 --> 00:27:46,171
Great! Come on, out you come.

335
00:27:48,854 --> 00:27:51,776
Come on, come on.

336
00:27:57,947 --> 00:28:00,155
We're evacuating camp, and in a hurry.

337
00:28:03,119 --> 00:28:04,392
And with very good reason.

338
00:28:08,073 --> 00:28:08,873
Show me, show me, show me.

339
00:28:09,450 --> 00:28:09,830
That one?

340
00:28:13,422 --> 00:28:16,173
That's one of the bombs that came out.

341
00:28:16,573 --> 00:28:20,438
We thought we were safe here, we were a long way away, and it landed here.

342
00:28:21,927 --> 00:28:25,261
That would have killed you instantly.

343
00:28:26,956 --> 00:28:28,429
So I think we should all go now.

344
00:28:33,552 --> 00:28:35,940
George's mission has come to an abrupt end.

345
00:28:41,303 --> 00:28:45,315
In the calm of the jungle night, Gordon's patience could be rewarded.

346
00:28:45,942 --> 00:28:49,572
Here he comes, here he comes, looks like a mole.

347
00:28:50,725 --> 00:28:53,506
I know it's not a mole, but it's very hard to tell what he is.

348
00:28:55,028 --> 00:28:57,530
God, my heart is beating out of my chest, come on!

349
00:28:58,220 --> 00:29:01,185
Please, please, please... oh, there he is, there he is, there he is!

350
00:29:02,315 --> 00:29:03,505
You little beauty!

351
00:29:04,538 --> 00:29:06,002
What is that?

352
00:29:08,499 --> 00:29:09,141
Gosh.

353
00:29:11,568 --> 00:29:13,236
I haven't got a clue what he is.

354
00:29:17,047 --> 00:29:17,857
That's weird.

355
00:29:18,604 --> 00:29:19,696
That is so weird.

356
00:29:20,879 --> 00:29:25,875
OK, if he just comes out a bit more, I can get an idea of his body shape,

357
00:29:25,995 --> 00:29:29,659
but... you can see his teeth...

358
00:29:30,039 --> 00:29:32,933
his eyes are shining like that because of this infrared light

359
00:29:33,147 --> 00:29:34,608
bouncing straight back at me.

360
00:29:36,580 --> 00:29:38,261
What a pretty animal.

361
00:29:40,829 --> 00:29:43,771
OK, out you come, come on, come on, please, just come out.

362
00:29:45,061 --> 00:29:47,920
Gosh, look at that.

363
00:29:50,349 --> 00:29:53,410
Oh, gosh, no, I think he's trying to go off—

364
00:29:53,456 --> 00:29:55,351
he's going to try and grab a limb

365
00:29:56,556 --> 00:29:57,515
and go off, oh, there.

366
00:29:59,717 --> 00:30:02,529
There could well be new species living here in the crater,

367
00:30:02,922 --> 00:30:07,364
and my job is to get shots of them, and let Kris try and identify them.

368
00:30:10,648 --> 00:30:14,262
Whatever it is, it appears to have no fear of people.

369
00:30:15,551 --> 00:30:16,837
If unique to the crater,

370
00:30:17,817 --> 00:30:21,161
it would help prove just how special the jungles of Bosavi are.

371
00:30:51,539 --> 00:30:53,358
Whilst Gordon is deep in the jungle,

372
00:30:54,611 --> 00:30:55,744
Steve is on the river.

373
00:30:58,281 --> 00:31:00,422
No-one knows what may lurk here at night.

374
00:31:03,762 --> 00:31:05,272
Eughh! Look!

375
00:31:05,965 --> 00:31:10,050
Whoa! They've been roosting just in the branches above us so as we've

376
00:31:10,077 --> 00:31:13,976
come across with our torches and lights, it's given them a shock.

377
00:31:15,191 --> 00:31:18,150
Steve is being mobbed by torrent flycatchers,

378
00:31:18,570 --> 00:31:20,243
birds found only in New Guinea.

379
00:31:27,696 --> 00:31:30,918
Eughh! It just flew right into my face.

380
00:31:34,846 --> 00:31:38,924
It may be wet, but no-one imagined there would be ducks in the jungle.

381
00:31:41,731 --> 00:31:44,934
Now that is something I really didn't expect to see!

382
00:31:45,842 --> 00:31:49,344
Salvadori's teal—unique to the mountain rivers of New Guinea.

383
00:31:50,195 --> 00:31:52,341
They almost look like they're just enjoying the rapids!

384
00:31:59,266 --> 00:32:02,169
That is a glorious looking little tree frog.

385
00:32:07,323 --> 00:32:07,977
Off he goes.

386
00:32:14,060 --> 00:32:16,949
Wow! These are actually torrent breeding frogs,

387
00:32:16,974 --> 00:32:19,637
so they love breeding in fast-flowing water like this.

388
00:32:20,531 --> 00:32:22,365
Let's see if we can get a glance

389
00:32:24,441 --> 00:32:26,742
at what makes this frog really special.

390
00:32:27,368 --> 00:32:33,018
That eyelid is laced through with a network of veins...

391
00:32:34,389 --> 00:32:36,595
and it's absolutely beautiful.

392
00:32:37,403 --> 00:32:39,398
He's got a face that you just can't help but love,

393
00:32:40,100 --> 00:32:43,451
and you know that any second, although he's sitting comfortably on my finger here,

394
00:32:43,504 --> 00:32:47,110
he could, without a single warning, just spring away and be gone.

395
00:32:49,093 --> 00:32:52,070
Come on, go and find yourself a...girlfriend.

396
00:32:59,008 --> 00:33:00,752
Not the! Not the ear!

397
00:33:11,867 --> 00:33:15,538
Mount Bosavi is so large it generates its own weather.

398
00:33:16,525 --> 00:33:18,406
For much of the night it's been raining,

399
00:33:19,193 --> 00:33:20,759
and the sleeping area is flooding.

400
00:33:22,190 --> 00:33:23,791
There's no respite from the mud.

401
00:33:30,918 --> 00:33:33,915
And it's tinned spaghetti for breakfast, again.

402
00:33:42,869 --> 00:33:45,732
Bosavi's forests extend right up to the summit.

403
00:33:46,870 --> 00:33:51,229
A vertical kilometre above Steve and Gordon, the jungle is much wetter.

404
00:33:56,057 --> 00:33:57,976
George is joining the team on the mountain.

405
00:33:58,551 --> 00:34:02,050
His mission... to explore the cloud forest clinging to the summit.

406
00:34:02,584 --> 00:34:05,118
Being one of the world's leading experts on insects,

407
00:34:05,580 --> 00:34:08,062
if there's anything unusual, he'll find it.

408
00:34:09,333 --> 00:34:13,279
This volcano is just like... like an island in the sky.

409
00:34:13,526 --> 00:34:17,060
I mean, it's 9,000 feet above sea level.

410
00:34:17,700 --> 00:34:19,587
Look at that wall!

411
00:34:20,895 --> 00:34:23,078
God, that is unbelievable.

412
00:34:25,009 --> 00:34:29,214
But as you can see, the weather's really very cloudy.

413
00:34:29,568 --> 00:34:31,021
It's amazing how it changes...

414
00:34:31,452 --> 00:34:34,541
incredibly heavy rain, very dark, and then just a little...

415
00:34:35,332 --> 00:34:37,107
a little gap in the cloud cover there.

416
00:34:38,147 --> 00:34:42,002
So it's touch and go whether we'll be able to land there.

417
00:34:48,237 --> 00:34:49,370
We're gonna make it.

418
00:34:51,040 --> 00:34:53,157
We're clear to land, we're clear to land.

419
00:34:58,315 --> 00:34:59,755
Oh... yeah, we're here!

420
00:35:02,012 --> 00:35:03,160
Fantastic.

421
00:35:05,546 --> 00:35:10,197
This precarious cliff edge will be George's camp for the next couple of days.

422
00:35:18,876 --> 00:35:22,619
A thousand metres below him, they're on the look out for new animals.

423
00:35:23,488 --> 00:35:25,885
Top of their list—the unknown cuscus.

424
00:35:31,012 --> 00:35:32,086
They search every hole...

425
00:35:34,316 --> 00:35:36,417
Every nook and every cranny...

426
00:35:36,691 --> 00:35:38,637
Mate, this place is leech central.

427
00:35:40,512 --> 00:35:46,058
On the summit, George is out exploring the peculiar mountain moss forest for the first time.

428
00:35:46,957 --> 00:35:48,564
He's stepped into another world.

429
00:35:49,817 --> 00:35:52,354
It's like Lord Of The Rings habitat.

430
00:35:53,298 --> 00:35:55,924
You'd expect orcs and elves appearing any minute.

431
00:35:56,697 --> 00:36:01,240
The whole forest is just humid, 100% humidity all the time,

432
00:36:01,993 --> 00:36:06,321
and this may look like solid ground, but it's not.

433
00:36:06,994 --> 00:36:09,795
Look, I can go through there and beyond.

434
00:36:09,820 --> 00:36:12,738
I can put my hand... I can go, probably,

435
00:36:12,794 --> 00:36:16,670
I can put my whole arm right through up to the hilt

436
00:36:16,695 --> 00:36:19,825
and that's just roots and soil and space,

437
00:36:21,058 --> 00:36:22,313
and that's what we're standing on.

438
00:36:22,399 --> 00:36:24,717
The whole thing is just a sort of...

439
00:36:26,312 --> 00:36:29,442
a mirage, almost, of plants and soil,

440
00:36:29,496 --> 00:36:32,212
but the soil's really interesting because the soil isn't just here,

441
00:36:32,266 --> 00:36:34,725
it actually occurs up on the plants as well.

442
00:36:34,965 --> 00:36:36,711
So it's actually aerial soil—

443
00:36:36,798 --> 00:36:41,470
all of this is just growing on a single thin branch.

444
00:36:41,524 --> 00:36:46,987
It's a huge carpet of moss and soil.

445
00:36:49,144 --> 00:36:52,483
It's almost like a different world.

446
00:36:54,761 --> 00:36:57,129
I haven't seen that one before.

447
00:36:59,590 --> 00:37:04,189
I mean, decay just brings fungi, bacteria, mosses—

448
00:37:04,529 --> 00:37:06,979
just everything is feeding off what's here.

449
00:37:07,004 --> 00:37:09,243
And look at that, that is the most exquisite

450
00:37:10,620 --> 00:37:15,697
tiny fungus growing on a dwarf bamboo, and it is just incredible.

451
00:37:19,825 --> 00:37:21,042
Ooh, look, look!

452
00:37:21,935 --> 00:37:23,790
Good God, look at that!

453
00:37:24,190 --> 00:37:25,560
I just saw that there in the ground.

454
00:37:26,154 --> 00:37:27,380
It's huge!

455
00:37:28,293 --> 00:37:29,100
This is a flatworm.

456
00:37:30,490 --> 00:37:33,719
Well, that's exactly the sort of animal you'd expect to find

457
00:37:33,752 --> 00:37:37,742
in this constantly wet environment.

458
00:37:38,158 --> 00:37:44,169
Flatworms come in all shapes and sizes... that's the underside...

459
00:37:45,076 --> 00:37:48,299
but I have never seen a flatworm this big before.

460
00:37:49,539 --> 00:37:50,798
It's absolutely amazing.

461
00:37:51,884 --> 00:37:54,770
Tiny little head end, that's the head end there.

462
00:37:56,267 --> 00:38:00,506
This habitat is incredibly special, because there are animals and plants here

463
00:38:00,546 --> 00:38:06,289
orchids and insects and higher animals you won't find anywhere else in the world.

464
00:38:06,682 --> 00:38:09,228
But also because it occupies a very, very small area

465
00:38:09,535 --> 00:38:11,117
and with increased global warming,

466
00:38:11,477 --> 00:38:14,839
that area will get smaller and smaller and smaller and eventually it'll all be gone.

467
00:38:19,670 --> 00:38:23,891
In the crater, one of the trackers has returned to camp with a wild animal,

468
00:38:24,365 --> 00:38:25,592
and it's totally trusting.

469
00:38:27,548 --> 00:38:28,942
Oh, wow!

470
00:38:31,040 --> 00:38:35,026
Oh, my goodness, he's absolutely beautiful. Come on little fella.

471
00:38:35,180 --> 00:38:36,117
I think it's our guy.

472
00:38:37,285 --> 00:38:39,667
I'm going to look in his mouth in a bit and we'll know from his teeth

473
00:38:39,767 --> 00:38:41,131
but this looks right on.

474
00:38:41,184 --> 00:38:44,232
This is a dark-furred cuscus, it's a montane cuscus.

475
00:38:44,807 --> 00:38:47,400
It's very much like the skull I suspected.

476
00:38:47,911 --> 00:38:50,803
The skull was similar to a different species called the silky cuscus,

477
00:38:50,850 --> 00:38:54,069
and the body is too, you can feel that silky fur.

478
00:38:54,365 --> 00:38:55,418
It's really, really thick.

479
00:38:55,443 --> 00:38:58,035
I guess this has adapted to living in a mountain environment.

480
00:38:58,215 --> 00:39:00,335
That's right. That's right. He seems to like you.

481
00:39:00,401 --> 00:39:04,038
He's got a very, very strong, but not actually unpleasant, smell.

482
00:39:04,093 --> 00:39:05,626
But it does hit you.

483
00:39:06,732 --> 00:39:09,694
This is the mammal that Gordon filmed emerging from the tree stump.

484
00:39:12,062 --> 00:39:13,921
I'm calling this the Bosavi cuscus,

485
00:39:14,561 --> 00:39:17,398
because I really think it has a lot of distinctive features.

486
00:39:17,445 --> 00:39:20,593
We're gonna find out more as we look closer, but...

487
00:39:20,898 --> 00:39:24,612
I just... I can't even begin to describe how it feels

488
00:39:24,639 --> 00:39:28,408
to have an animal in my hands that is this beautiful and,

489
00:39:29,215 --> 00:39:31,934
in all probability, has never been seen before by science.

490
00:39:31,994 --> 00:39:38,061
I think what we have is a cuscus that long ago has been isolated on this volcano

491
00:39:38,515 --> 00:39:43,917
and has just not been able to have any contact with any of its relatives and

492
00:39:43,964 --> 00:39:48,175
has become something here in isolation that is unique to Bosavi.

493
00:39:48,415 --> 00:39:52,101
He's totally chilled out. He's got no idea quite how important he is.

494
00:39:53,360 --> 00:39:56,219
- So gorgeous. - Yeah! Little guy!

495
00:39:57,125 --> 00:39:58,947
You're a major scientific discovery.

496
00:40:01,496 --> 00:40:02,835
How about that?

497
00:40:03,868 --> 00:40:07,037
I travel the world looking for new species in many different places

498
00:40:07,537 --> 00:40:11,909
and we find new mammals, it still does happen, but so many of them,

499
00:40:12,116 --> 00:40:15,283
most of them are things like bats and rodents, and to find something,

500
00:40:15,397 --> 00:40:20,273
a marsupial, an animal that's this size is really exciting,

501
00:40:20,313 --> 00:40:22,885
it's a cause for a major celebration.

502
00:40:23,519 --> 00:40:27,931
Crack open the champagne, or crack open the bully beef!

503
00:40:30,981 --> 00:40:35,553
It's a brand new sub-species of cuscus, and Bosavi is its only home.

504
00:40:36,148 --> 00:40:40,035
If these jungles are logged, we'll lose animals like this forever.

505
00:40:45,048 --> 00:40:47,767
In the depths of the crater, it's raining again.

506
00:40:50,431 --> 00:40:52,139
It's been a long, hard expedition.

507
00:40:53,974 --> 00:40:55,928
Exhaustion and illness are setting in.

508
00:40:58,843 --> 00:41:03,045
There's been an outbreak of intestinal worms in the camp,

509
00:41:03,212 --> 00:41:05,577
so we're all taking these worming tablets

510
00:41:05,624 --> 00:41:09,198
which will pretty much kill everything we've got in our guts.

511
00:41:10,352 --> 00:41:11,802
Makes you feel really run down,

512
00:41:13,598 --> 00:41:15,528
but this tablet just kills everything.

513
00:41:18,634 --> 00:41:20,462
Leeches are infesting camp.

514
00:41:26,562 --> 00:41:30,248
No-one imagined just how rich this mountain would turn out to be.

515
00:41:35,022 --> 00:41:37,817
In the weird moss forest that clings to the rim of the crater,

516
00:41:39,457 --> 00:41:40,611
George is setting a trap.

517
00:41:44,159 --> 00:41:47,070
It's carefully positioned, right on the cliff edge.

518
00:42:03,407 --> 00:42:07,179
Once night falls, a high-powered light bulb will be switched on

519
00:42:07,213 --> 00:42:08,868
to attract insects to the sheet.

520
00:42:11,685 --> 00:42:15,852
And that's going to be...hopefully, it's going to be heaving with bugs.

521
00:42:20,729 --> 00:42:24,454
In the crater, Gordon and Steve head off in opposite directions.

522
00:42:24,878 --> 00:42:27,384
In the hope finding more distinguishable mammals.

523
00:42:27,853 --> 00:42:29,507
They search all night if they have to.

524
00:42:32,842 --> 00:42:35,690
They have no idea what's live on there in the darkness.

525
00:42:52,612 --> 00:42:56,096
At night, the jungle has its own special magic.

526
00:42:59,315 --> 00:43:02,352
This tree is covered in bracket fungus,

527
00:43:03,018 --> 00:43:06,930
and you can see all the tiny little spores being discharged,

528
00:43:07,479 --> 00:43:10,016
it makes it look as if they're actually steaming.

529
00:43:16,581 --> 00:43:20,762
In the early hours, Kris finds another animal with no fear of humans.

530
00:43:21,800 --> 00:43:23,409
It looks like a giant hamster,

531
00:43:24,671 --> 00:43:25,865
but it's a painted ringtail.

532
00:43:26,258 --> 00:43:28,899
Oh, he's absolutely gorgeous!

533
00:43:28,950 --> 00:43:32,585
Not a new species, but definitely one of the most beautiful animals

534
00:43:32,672 --> 00:43:33,709
that lives in this forest.

535
00:43:33,742 --> 00:43:35,189
Gosh, he really is.

536
00:43:35,475 --> 00:43:38,392
The fur is just exquisite.

537
00:43:38,485 --> 00:43:41,718
It is just so dense and so soft.

538
00:43:42,408 --> 00:43:44,890
You can see at night time this place just comes alive.

539
00:43:45,417 --> 00:43:48,835
We've done so much walking about this forest finding nothing,

540
00:43:48,895 --> 00:43:52,672
and you only have to find something like this and it makes it all worthwhile.

541
00:43:52,706 --> 00:43:54,974
You forget all that misery and all that hardship.

542
00:43:58,493 --> 00:44:01,965
On the cliff edge, George can hardly believe his eyes.

543
00:44:05,047 --> 00:44:06,578
I'm just overwhelmed.

544
00:44:06,682 --> 00:44:12,331
I never imagined I'd see such a diversity of moth.

545
00:44:12,756 --> 00:44:16,577
I mean, some of these things I've never seen before in my life.

546
00:44:17,517 --> 00:44:23,004
The variety of moths here is absolutely staggering!

547
00:44:23,253 --> 00:44:27,356
There's geometrids, hawkmoths, there's fruit piercing moths,

548
00:44:27,796 --> 00:44:30,247
and it's raining, it's tipping it down!

549
00:44:31,334 --> 00:44:32,264
This shouldn't be happening,

550
00:44:32,497 --> 00:44:37,925
and these bulbs only work in a radius of about 200 yards.

551
00:44:38,665 --> 00:44:44,003
All this has come from a 200 yard radius to this bulb.

552
00:44:44,690 --> 00:44:49,186
Can you imagine how rich this forest actually is?

553
00:44:49,705 --> 00:44:51,939
Almost beyond my understanding.

554
00:44:52,407 --> 00:44:53,473
Look at that.

555
00:44:54,340 --> 00:44:57,823
I'm absolutely...incredulous.

556
00:44:58,945 --> 00:45:00,073
My God, look at it!

557
00:45:01,114 --> 00:45:03,735
Look at that one, that brassy gold colour.

558
00:45:10,955 --> 00:45:13,641
In the crater, Steve discovered a monster,

559
00:45:14,321 --> 00:45:15,209
a tarantula.

560
00:45:19,130 --> 00:45:20,557
Look at that!

561
00:45:21,802 --> 00:45:24,637
The way he's tilted back there, you can see he's rocked back

562
00:45:26,235 --> 00:45:28,164
in order to bring those fangs into position

563
00:45:28,225 --> 00:45:30,518
so he can bring down the entire bodyweight,

564
00:45:31,127 --> 00:45:33,888
plunging those fangs into whatever it is that's annoying him.

565
00:45:35,634 --> 00:45:36,387
Come on then.

566
00:45:37,674 --> 00:45:39,171
Now don't go, don't go.

567
00:45:40,618 --> 00:45:42,952
I do have to be careful here, I'd be a lot more ambitious

568
00:45:43,999 --> 00:45:45,602
if I knew what it was

569
00:45:46,636 --> 00:45:47,490
and if we were in a...

570
00:45:48,713 --> 00:45:50,072
less remote environment.

571
00:45:52,787 --> 00:45:54,422
But to get bitten or stung by something

572
00:45:55,884 --> 00:45:57,097
like this out here...

573
00:46:00,145 --> 00:46:01,169
..could be really sketchy.

574
00:46:05,497 --> 00:46:10,635
I have never been anywhere where I've seen the diversity of moths that I'm seeing here.

575
00:46:11,164 --> 00:46:14,934
If you'd told me, I wouldn't have believed you, but it's here.

576
00:46:15,805 --> 00:46:18,017
That's a different one. That's a different hawkmoth.

577
00:46:18,664 --> 00:46:20,332
That's a different one come in now, just now.

578
00:46:21,026 --> 00:46:25,260
V-shaped wings, very fast flyers, really strong moths.

579
00:46:25,627 --> 00:46:27,181
Fantastic colouration there.

580
00:46:27,782 --> 00:46:29,483
Oh, look now, there's a hawkmoth too.

581
00:46:29,515 --> 00:46:31,148
Now, I've never seen that one before.

582
00:46:31,572 --> 00:46:33,539
What percentage of these will be new?

583
00:46:35,138 --> 00:46:36,432
It could easily be...

584
00:46:37,942 --> 00:46:42,235
a quarter, it could easily be a quarter of them.

585
00:46:42,962 --> 00:46:45,897
It's called an arctiid moth and when it's annoyed,

586
00:46:47,405 --> 00:46:52,819
it produces very horrible-smelling fluid from the thorax.

587
00:46:52,946 --> 00:46:54,579
There, see that? Look at that!

588
00:46:55,945 --> 00:46:57,062
That is amazing!

589
00:46:57,643 --> 00:46:58,819
What a defence.

590
00:46:59,752 --> 00:47:01,445
And that tastes really foul.

591
00:47:05,462 --> 00:47:07,095
Yuk, yuk.

592
00:47:07,884 --> 00:47:10,424
Even if I'd had to walk up here on my hands and knees,

593
00:47:10,498 --> 00:47:11,891
it would have been worth it for this.

594
00:47:12,164 --> 00:47:15,475
This one hour of moth mayhem.

595
00:47:17,912 --> 00:47:22,862
A haul of unique creatures like this proves Bosavi's forests are priceless.

596
00:47:25,274 --> 00:47:25,747
Honestly!

597
00:47:32,890 --> 00:47:34,671
Gordon gets a shout from a tracker.

598
00:47:46,150 --> 00:47:49,309
Oh, my word, have a look at this!

599
00:47:50,376 --> 00:47:56,977
Oh, gosh, that is the biggest rat I have ever seen.

600
00:47:57,191 --> 00:47:59,097
That is a murid rat, a true rat,

601
00:47:59,198 --> 00:48:02,472
the same family as the rats you find in cities and sewers.

602
00:48:02,512 --> 00:48:04,338
You've got a big smile on your face.

603
00:48:04,597 --> 00:48:08,703
The reason I'm smiling is because this is absolutely a new species.

604
00:48:08,777 --> 00:48:10,485
This is something that doesn't have a scientific name.

605
00:48:10,685 --> 00:48:13,668
This is one of the largest rats in the world, and here we are,

606
00:48:14,823 --> 00:48:15,290
holding it.

607
00:48:16,224 --> 00:48:18,811
I just think it's an amazing creature,

608
00:48:18,937 --> 00:48:22,633
found nowhere else on the entire planet.

609
00:48:23,067 --> 00:48:25,308
That is such a huge deal.

610
00:48:25,627 --> 00:48:28,962
And this animal is so chilled out, look at him, he's just grooming.

611
00:48:30,020 --> 00:48:33,462
You can tell it's a rat but yet it looks just so different from

612
00:48:33,502 --> 00:48:34,821
any rat you've ever seen, right?

613
00:48:34,934 --> 00:48:39,229
Yeah. I had a cat, and the cat was about the same size as this rat.

614
00:48:39,556 --> 00:48:43,782
Any cat that you buy to catch rats is going to run a mile

615
00:48:43,850 --> 00:48:44,689
from something like this.

616
00:48:44,923 --> 00:48:48,282
Mount Bosavi's such a big mountain, it's largely unexplored,

617
00:48:48,310 --> 00:48:51,954
it's so isolated that truly, some of the things we are finding

618
00:48:52,101 --> 00:48:54,480
are new species and are spectacular new species.

619
00:48:54,921 --> 00:48:57,359
Big rats, cuscus, fantastic animals.

620
00:48:57,660 --> 00:49:01,152
It gave me the heebie-jeebies, the thought of a giant rat and

621
00:49:01,179 --> 00:49:05,053
I've been going down the holes in hollow trees looking for big things,

622
00:49:05,089 --> 00:49:08,218
and it's actually kept me awake at night and here he is, he's just...

623
00:49:08,839 --> 00:49:10,660
oh, he's like a little puppy.

624
00:49:18,600 --> 00:49:21,082
New species of giant woolly rat!

625
00:49:21,392 --> 00:49:23,392
- No! - Yeah.

626
00:49:24,219 --> 00:49:27,169
That's unbelievable. Or are you just making it up?

627
00:49:27,276 --> 00:49:29,037
No, no, we got it, we got it, yeah.

628
00:49:29,910 --> 00:49:32,014
God, it was great, so great.

629
00:49:33,214 --> 00:49:35,275
The biggest rat in the world.

630
00:49:35,649 --> 00:49:36,712
Was it in a trap or was it...?

631
00:49:36,737 --> 00:49:39,996
No, just running about the forest, tame as anything.

632
00:49:41,058 --> 00:49:41,797
That's incredible.

633
00:49:47,479 --> 00:49:50,539
It's time to pack up and collect George from the summit.

634
00:49:57,792 --> 00:50:02,225
As I stand here, just about to be whisked away by this helicopter,

635
00:50:02,250 --> 00:50:04,618
I realise that my grandchildren

636
00:50:05,017 --> 00:50:10,444
may not ever be able to see this sort of habitat or the animals and plants that live here.

637
00:50:10,718 --> 00:50:11,593
It could all be gone.

638
00:50:13,180 --> 00:50:15,288
Now all their findings will be brought together

639
00:50:16,568 --> 00:50:18,405
and presented to the outside world.

640
00:50:19,982 --> 00:50:22,066
With the help of a remarkable tribe,

641
00:50:22,586 --> 00:50:25,107
they've found hundreds of spectacular creatures.

642
00:50:29,792 --> 00:50:31,507
He is just a parrot in miniature.

643
00:50:33,105 --> 00:50:36,119
That is absolutely gorgeous!

644
00:50:37,062 --> 00:50:39,565
They've discovered over 40 new species,

645
00:50:40,228 --> 00:50:41,647
from exquisite geckos

646
00:50:43,087 --> 00:50:44,287
to magical moths

647
00:50:46,083 --> 00:50:47,356
and bizarre frogs.

648
00:50:48,616 --> 00:50:50,944
And they've made major scientific discoveries...

649
00:50:51,451 --> 00:50:53,232
creatures with no fear of people.

650
00:50:53,413 --> 00:50:55,165
Oh, he's like a little puppy!

651
00:50:57,180 --> 00:50:58,999
Mammals that no-one knew existed.

652
00:51:00,372 --> 00:51:05,557
Wow! It's so incredibly rare that new species of mammal

653
00:51:05,666 --> 00:51:07,379
are found around the world these days.

654
00:51:07,426 --> 00:51:10,207
This has got to be one of the most incredible moments of my life.

655
00:51:11,623 --> 00:51:14,649
All of this on one amazing mountain.

656
00:51:15,765 --> 00:51:19,505
The hope is that Mount Bosavi, once a forgotten corner,

657
00:51:20,285 --> 00:51:21,880
will now become known around the world

658
00:51:22,707 --> 00:51:25,979
and protected as a unique rainforest of global importance.

